00:40:04.160 --> 00:40:06.290
You're probably also missing
a lot of the diversity.

00:40:06.290 --> 00:40:08.180
And there's some very
unusual reefs in Honduras

00:40:08.180 --> 00:40:10.580
that we've already decided
to place some bets on and try

00:40:10.580 --> 00:40:12.410
to make sure that
those unusual reefs are

00:40:12.410 --> 00:40:14.250
part of that portfolio.

00:40:14.250 --> 00:40:16.010
So in general, absolutely, yes.

00:40:16.010 --> 00:40:18.551
We're also working with a lot
of the partners throughout that

00:40:18.551 --> 00:40:20.870
region-- governments,
NGOs, others, funders--

00:40:20.870 --> 00:40:24.200
to think about how do we
get this solution at scale.

00:40:24.200 --> 00:40:26.570
And so every step is
in that direction.

00:40:26.570 --> 00:40:29.360
The next level is going
to be a tailored analysis

00:40:29.360 --> 00:40:30.830
to that particular
region, looking

00:40:30.830 --> 00:40:33.410
at the connectivity matrix,
the distribution of habitat

00:40:33.410 --> 00:40:34.192
for that region.

00:40:34.192 --> 00:40:36.650
And then analyzing that compared
to the work that's already

00:40:36.650 --> 00:40:39.605
going on, and saying, how
does the current distribution

00:40:39.605 --> 00:40:42.350
of effort perform over time?

00:40:42.350 --> 00:40:44.720
And are there areas where if
we expanded our effort just

00:40:44.720 --> 00:40:47.690
a little bit, we could get
really big bang for our buck

00:40:47.690 --> 00:40:51.650
in terms of adaptation
of the system as a whole?

00:40:51.650 --> 00:40:55.410
AUDIENCE: Are we talking
something as big as maybe

00:40:55.410 --> 00:40:57.282
transplantation?

00:40:57.282 --> 00:40:58.990
MICHAEL WEBSTER: That's
a great question.

00:40:58.990 --> 00:41:02.430
I didn't talk about it
specifically in this talk.

00:41:02.430 --> 00:41:05.790
But it is an area that's
getting more and more attention

00:41:05.790 --> 00:41:07.010
in our field.

00:41:07.010 --> 00:41:10.920
And it's a very direct way of
trying to solve this problem.

00:41:10.920 --> 00:41:13.440
If the corals are
declining on a reef,

00:41:13.440 --> 00:41:15.060
and you want corals
on that reef,

00:41:15.060 --> 00:41:16.920
what if you just
grow some corals

00:41:16.920 --> 00:41:19.297
and put them on that reef?

00:41:19.297 --> 00:41:20.880
And the thinking on
it is very linear.

00:41:20.880 --> 00:41:24.210
And we have every reason to
believe that that can be done.

00:41:24.210 --> 00:41:26.590
And people have done
it over and over again.

00:41:26.590 --> 00:41:29.230
The problem with it
is a scaling problem.

00:41:29.230 --> 00:41:32.007
So we did a back-of-the-envelope
analysis on that Mesoamerican

00:41:32.007 --> 00:41:33.840
region, which is just
a little tiny fraction

00:41:33.840 --> 00:41:35.310
of the world's coral reefs.

00:41:35.310 --> 00:41:38.095
And we looked at how many
corals cover a certain area

00:41:38.095 --> 00:41:39.970
on the bottom, and how
much habitat, and just

00:41:39.970 --> 00:41:42.930
said, how many coral
colonies are in that region?

00:41:42.930 --> 00:41:45.715
And the answer ends up
being probably billions.

00:41:45.715 --> 00:41:48.510
So there's probably
billions of these colonies.

00:41:48.510 --> 00:41:52.330
To do transplantation is
very expensive per unit.

00:41:52.330 --> 00:41:53.994
So if you're going
to collect a coral,

00:41:53.994 --> 00:41:55.410
you're going to
grow it in a tank,

00:41:55.410 --> 00:41:57.570
you're going to run the energy
to keep that tank moving.

00:41:57.570 --> 00:41:58.890
You're going to
get it to a size.

00:41:58.890 --> 00:42:00.600
You're going to take it
as a diver underwater,

00:42:00.600 --> 00:42:02.160
and you're going to
put it on the bottom.

00:42:02.160 --> 00:42:03.576
Each and every one
of those corals

00:42:03.576 --> 00:42:06.900
is going to cost you
$1, or $10, or more.

00:42:06.900 --> 00:42:08.970
Most of the
transplantation experiments

00:42:08.970 --> 00:42:10.620
that have been done
so far tend to work

00:42:10.620 --> 00:42:13.140
in tens of individual
corals, or hundreds

00:42:13.140 --> 00:42:14.490
of individuals corals--

00:42:14.490 --> 00:42:16.860
or at the higher end, thousands.

00:42:16.860 --> 00:42:19.050
And it's probably
multiple orders

00:42:19.050 --> 00:42:21.750
of magnitude off the
scale that's really

00:42:21.750 --> 00:42:23.610
going to make a difference
to the population

00:42:23.610 --> 00:42:24.680
dynamics in this region.

00:42:24.680 --> 00:42:27.060
It's kind of like thinking
about humanity, right?

00:42:27.060 --> 00:42:29.980
Humanity has got somewhere
short of 10 billion people.

00:42:29.980 --> 00:42:32.670
How many new people would
you have to add to the planet

00:42:32.670 --> 00:42:34.660
to really change our
population dynamics?

00:42:34.660 --> 00:42:36.390
It's not going to
be a few thousand.

00:42:36.390 --> 00:42:39.270
It would have to be a much,
much larger number than that.

00:42:39.270 --> 00:42:41.070
And so while I think
there's a lot going

00:42:41.070 --> 00:42:43.620
on that's promising on
the restoration front,

00:42:43.620 --> 00:42:46.862
there hasn't been a real ability
to solve the scaling problem.

00:42:46.862 --> 00:42:49.320
A lot of people are working
at, how do you make it cheaper,

00:42:49.320 --> 00:42:51.730
and cheaper, and cheaper,
so that you can do more?

00:42:51.730 --> 00:42:53.684
And I think there's
some promise in that.

00:42:53.684 --> 00:42:56.100
The other side of it that's
interesting on the restoration

00:42:56.100 --> 00:42:58.110
front is that
people are beginning

00:42:58.110 --> 00:42:59.500
to say, wait a minute.

00:42:59.500 --> 00:43:02.310
What if we identify some
of those unusual corals?

00:43:02.310 --> 00:43:03.780
And what if we put
those corals out

00:43:03.780 --> 00:43:06.757
there, and essentially speed
up the adaptation process?

00:43:06.757 --> 00:43:08.340
Let's pick the winners
for the future.

00:43:08.340 --> 00:43:10.650
Let's grow those ones-- like
the really temperature-tolerant

00:43:10.650 --> 00:43:11.280
corals--

00:43:11.280 --> 00:43:12.960
and put those out on the reef.

00:43:12.960 --> 00:43:15.450
I think that's more
promising, but one

00:43:15.450 --> 00:43:17.100
of the things that
our analysis shows

00:43:17.100 --> 00:43:19.200
on the different
strategies is that when

00:43:19.200 --> 00:43:21.540
you start picking a
narrow set of winners,

00:43:21.540 --> 00:43:23.370
that's when you start
to get into trouble.

00:43:23.370 --> 00:43:25.320
Because that's when
your assumptions are

00:43:25.320 --> 00:43:26.190
likely to be wrong.

00:43:26.190 --> 00:43:28.320
What you could do, if you
wanted to pick the most

00:43:28.320 --> 00:43:30.540
temperature-tolerant corals,
is you could essentially

00:43:30.540 --> 00:43:32.610
create a monoculture problem.

00:43:32.610 --> 00:43:35.100
You could select those corals
for that particular trait,

00:43:35.100 --> 00:43:37.697
but you might be losing
other traits in that process.

00:43:37.697 --> 00:43:39.280
We know how to do
this in agriculture.

00:43:39.280 --> 00:43:41.905
And this is one of the problems
we've gotten to in agriculture,

00:43:41.905 --> 00:43:44.880
is by designing plants
or animals for very, very

00:43:44.880 --> 00:43:47.609
specific purposes, they
become bad at other things.

00:43:47.609 --> 00:43:49.650
And so you might be able
to design a coral that's

00:43:49.650 --> 00:43:51.540
really good at dealing
with high temperature,

00:43:51.540 --> 00:43:53.640
but maybe it's
susceptible to disease.

00:43:53.640 --> 00:43:55.526
Or maybe it doesn't
do well in storms.

00:43:55.526 --> 00:43:57.900
And it's the combination of
these different traits, which

00:43:57.900 --> 00:43:59.316
is probably going
to be what we're

00:43:59.316 --> 00:44:01.387
going to need for successful
reefs going forward.

00:44:01.387 --> 00:44:02.970
So I think we're
just beginning to ask

00:44:02.970 --> 00:44:04.920
some of the interesting
questions there about,

00:44:04.920 --> 00:44:07.800
can we actually drive
the evolution of corals

00:44:07.800 --> 00:44:09.829
by selecting for
particular traits?

00:44:09.829 --> 00:44:12.120
And can we do that in a way
that protects our diversity

00:44:12.120 --> 00:44:13.079
portfolio?

00:44:13.079 --> 00:44:15.120
What I would say is, for
protecting the diversity

00:44:15.120 --> 00:44:18.300
portfolio in the process, that's
a really good step forward.

00:44:18.300 --> 00:44:20.040
One of my concerns
about this area,

00:44:20.040 --> 00:44:23.010
though, is that the
resources we're currently

00:44:23.010 --> 00:44:25.650
putting into trying to
solve these problems locally

00:44:25.650 --> 00:44:28.106
could shift to trying
to grow corals.

00:44:28.106 --> 00:44:29.730
And if we haven't
resolved the problems

00:44:29.730 --> 00:44:32.400
that I was talking about earlier
around things like overfishing

00:44:32.400 --> 00:44:34.230
and pollution, we
don't actually have

00:44:34.230 --> 00:44:37.440
good environments to
transplant those corals into.

00:44:37.440 --> 00:44:39.600
So what I would recommend
is let's make sure

00:44:39.600 --> 00:44:40.730
that we're doing that work.

00:44:40.730 --> 00:44:43.090
Let's make sure we're creating
those good local environments

00:44:43.090 --> 00:44:44.940
that are going to allow
corals to flourish.

00:44:44.940 --> 00:44:49.140
And if we want to augment that
by restoring corals actively,

00:44:49.140 --> 00:44:49.860
let's do so.

00:44:49.860 --> 00:44:53.070
But let's not kid ourselves into
thinking that the costs of that

00:44:53.070 --> 00:44:56.407
are going to be small
or easily scalable.

00:44:56.407 --> 00:44:57.240
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:44:57.240 --> 00:44:59.070
So you mentioned
the village in Fiji.

00:44:59.070 --> 00:45:01.170
And a lot of us here
have to influence

00:45:01.170 --> 00:45:05.310
either our coworkers,
or outsiders, or users

00:45:05.310 --> 00:45:08.400
that there is a
better way to do X.

00:45:08.400 --> 00:45:10.484
But human nature is what it is.

00:45:10.484 --> 00:45:12.150
I wanted to understand
a little bit more

00:45:12.150 --> 00:45:15.900
about how you actually go about
from the sort of headline of,

00:45:15.900 --> 00:45:19.230
you can do just as well
with tourism than fishing.

00:45:19.230 --> 00:45:21.160
How do you actually
implement that?

00:45:21.160 --> 00:45:23.910
A little bit more on
the mechanics of that.

00:45:23.910 --> 00:45:26.400
MICHAEL WEBSTER: The
bulk of our program staff

00:45:26.400 --> 00:45:28.470
are what I would
loosely describe

00:45:28.470 --> 00:45:30.590
as community organizers.

00:45:30.590 --> 00:45:33.300
They are people who live in
Fiji, or they live in Honduras,

00:45:33.300 --> 00:45:34.860
and live in Indonesia.

00:45:34.860 --> 00:45:37.380
And they're part
of that community.

00:45:37.380 --> 00:45:39.030
And what they have
decided on their own

00:45:39.030 --> 00:45:42.150
is that they want to
be part of solutions

00:45:42.150 --> 00:45:44.820
that are going to benefit the
community for the long term.

00:45:44.820 --> 00:45:46.640
How do they manage
their activities?

00:45:46.640 --> 00:45:48.930
How do they have economic
development while continuing

00:45:48.930 --> 00:45:50.755
to have these other benefits?

00:45:50.755 --> 00:45:52.630
And one of the beautiful
things about working

00:45:52.630 --> 00:45:55.360
with that particular population
is that that population

00:45:55.360 --> 00:45:59.320
is actually quite keyed into
the interests and the incentives

00:45:59.320 --> 00:46:00.970
within that community.

00:46:00.970 --> 00:46:04.000
One of the big mistakes of sort
of conservation over the years

00:46:04.000 --> 00:46:06.070
has been the assumption
that people like me who

00:46:06.070 --> 00:46:08.142
are Western trained--
grew up in North America--

00:46:08.142 --> 00:46:10.600
that I better know what's best
for a community in Honduras.

00:46:10.600 --> 00:46:13.120
Or I'm going to know what's
best for a community in Fiji.

00:46:13.120 --> 00:46:14.320
The reality is, I don't.

00:46:14.320 --> 00:46:17.260
I can understand how
coral reefs work.

00:46:17.260 --> 00:46:19.690
I can understand what's
been tried in other places.

00:46:19.690 --> 00:46:21.580
But the community
actually has to be the one

00:46:21.580 --> 00:46:24.770
to think about what they
want for themselves.

00:46:24.770 --> 00:46:27.190
The key to making something
like this work usually,

00:46:27.190 --> 00:46:29.080
though, is trying
to find the place

00:46:29.080 --> 00:46:31.130
where the incentives line up.

00:46:31.130 --> 00:46:34.270
And if there's a strong
incentive within the community

00:46:34.270 --> 00:46:36.910
to try something
different or to reinforce

00:46:36.910 --> 00:46:38.650
something that's
different, that's

00:46:38.650 --> 00:46:39.790
when it's likely to work.

00:46:39.790 --> 00:46:41.420
And if those
incentives don't exist,

00:46:41.420 --> 00:46:43.480
it doesn't matter how
good your idea is.

00:46:43.480 --> 00:46:46.370
The community actually has to
be able to benefit from it.

00:46:46.370 --> 00:46:50.140
So in the Fijian
situation, that community--

00:46:50.140 --> 00:46:52.469
independently, they
knew they had a problem.

00:46:52.469 --> 00:46:54.760
They knew that they weren't
catching the fish that they

00:46:54.760 --> 00:46:55.802
used to be able to catch.

00:46:55.802 --> 00:46:58.010
The fishermen in the community
were saying, you know,

00:46:58.010 --> 00:46:58.810
when I was a kid--

00:46:58.810 --> 00:47:00.620
and they sort of
realized, wait a minute.

00:47:00.620 --> 00:47:01.511
What's going on?

00:47:01.511 --> 00:47:03.010
At the same time,
that community was

00:47:03.010 --> 00:47:05.560
seeing fishers come in from
other villages and fish

00:47:05.560 --> 00:47:06.760
their reefs.

00:47:06.760 --> 00:47:08.471
Now, in that case,
I told you there's

00:47:08.471 --> 00:47:10.720
a property right system,
where that community actually

00:47:10.720 --> 00:47:12.096
owns that resource.

00:47:12.096 --> 00:47:13.720
And they started to
say, wait a minute.

00:47:13.720 --> 00:47:15.560
This has gotten so bad.

00:47:15.560 --> 00:47:17.240
How do we solve this?

00:47:17.240 --> 00:47:19.630
How do we take action
for our own reefs

00:47:19.630 --> 00:47:22.420
in a way that allows us to
have the kinds of fishing

00:47:22.420 --> 00:47:24.512
we used to, and the kinds
of benefits we used to?

00:47:24.512 --> 00:47:26.470
And so they came to us
and other groups to say,

00:47:26.470 --> 00:47:28.370
can you help us figure this out?

00:47:28.370 --> 00:47:31.330
And so we'd seen, for
example, dive user fee systems

00:47:31.330 --> 00:47:33.050
work in other communities.

00:47:33.050 --> 00:47:34.600
So a community might
say, hey, we're

00:47:34.600 --> 00:47:37.457
going to make this particular
area of reef a protected area.

00:47:37.457 --> 00:47:39.040
And we're going to
allow it to fill up

00:47:39.040 --> 00:47:40.572
with sharks and big groupers.

00:47:40.572 --> 00:47:42.280
But if you want to
come here as a tourist

00:47:42.280 --> 00:47:43.480
and you want to see
that because you're

00:47:43.480 --> 00:47:45.160
interested in that
wildlife, we're

00:47:45.160 --> 00:47:47.290
going to charge you a
nominal fee to do it--

00:47:47.290 --> 00:47:50.174
maybe $10, maybe $20, and
then you can go and see that.

00:47:50.174 --> 00:47:52.090
Well, if you're paying
a bunch to be a tourist

00:47:52.090 --> 00:47:54.006
and go to a place like
this, it doesn't really

00:47:54.006 --> 00:47:55.180
matter, this small fee.

00:47:55.180 --> 00:47:57.730
But those small fees can be
really important to a community

00:47:57.730 --> 00:48:00.460
like this, because in the
case of the community in Fiji,

00:48:00.460 --> 00:48:02.920
some of those fees went directly
into community projects--

00:48:02.920 --> 00:48:05.050
like scholarships for
children, or like building

00:48:05.050 --> 00:48:06.550
a new community center.

00:48:06.550 --> 00:48:09.460
And that community could
then tie their interest

00:48:09.460 --> 00:48:13.720
in protecting the reef with
a direct economic gain.

00:48:13.720 --> 00:48:16.456
Those dollars also go
to managing the park.

00:48:16.456 --> 00:48:17.830
And so if you can
create a system

00:48:17.830 --> 00:48:19.010
like that where the
community is saying,

00:48:19.010 --> 00:48:20.450
hey, we want
something like this.

00:48:20.450 --> 00:48:25.210
We want a different set of
access to our resources.

00:48:25.210 --> 00:48:26.920
We see these benefits
on fisheries.

00:48:26.920 --> 00:48:28.760
We see these economic benefits.

00:48:28.760 --> 00:48:31.122
How do you design a
system to do that?

00:48:31.122 --> 00:48:33.580
Well, we've got good models
around the world of communities

00:48:33.580 --> 00:48:35.800
who have been down this road,
who have built these systems--

00:48:35.800 --> 00:48:37.383
who have built out
the business plans,

00:48:37.383 --> 00:48:39.700
who have built out the
enforcement mechanisms--

00:48:39.700 --> 00:48:42.820
so that you can apply those
same tools from one community

00:48:42.820 --> 00:48:44.020
to another community.

00:48:44.020 --> 00:48:46.720
But it absolutely
requires that initial step

00:48:46.720 --> 00:48:49.450
of a community that wants
to do something about this.

00:48:49.450 --> 00:48:51.490
It's much more difficult--
and frankly, it's

00:48:51.490 --> 00:48:53.470
not necessarily worth it--
to go into a community that's

00:48:53.470 --> 00:48:55.000
not looking to solve
a problem, that

00:48:55.000 --> 00:48:57.820
says everything is just fine,
and try and impose a solution.

00:48:57.820 --> 00:48:59.507
That doesn't make any sense.

00:48:59.507 --> 00:49:01.840
The market out there-- if
you're looking for communities

00:49:01.840 --> 00:49:04.720
that want to solve these kinds
of problems-- is really good.

00:49:04.720 --> 00:49:07.367
That's one of the blessings
and curses of our work,

00:49:07.367 --> 00:49:08.950
is that there are
more communities who

00:49:08.950 --> 00:49:10.930
want this kind of
solution than we

00:49:10.930 --> 00:49:13.960
have resources right now to be
able to help them design it.

00:49:13.960 --> 00:49:16.104
If every community has
to do this de novo--

00:49:16.104 --> 00:49:18.020
if they have to figure
it out for themselves--

00:49:18.020 --> 00:49:19.520
it's not going to
be very efficient.

00:49:19.520 --> 00:49:21.040
It's not going to
be very effective.

00:49:21.040 --> 00:49:23.750
If we can take what's
worked in other places

00:49:23.750 --> 00:49:25.900
and compare that to what
the individual needs

00:49:25.900 --> 00:49:27.670
of the community
are, we can find

00:49:27.670 --> 00:49:30.090
things that are more scalable.

00:49:30.090 --> 00:49:34.180
AUDIENCE: So you showed a
map of all the coral reefs

00:49:34.180 --> 00:49:35.050
around the world.

00:49:35.050 --> 00:49:37.330
And a lot of them
are centralized--

00:49:37.330 --> 00:49:41.950
I saw-- around the coastal
regions for United States.

00:49:41.950 --> 00:49:43.720
Yeah, that one.

00:49:43.720 --> 00:49:47.350
And then, you had also showed
a picture of the Maui issue,

00:49:47.350 --> 00:49:51.770
where we had the toxins coming
in, and also the sediments

00:49:51.770 --> 00:49:52.910
and the nutrients.

00:49:52.910 --> 00:49:56.270
But not from this
standpoint, what

00:49:56.270 --> 00:50:00.850
has the alliance done in terms
of legislation and potential

00:50:00.850 --> 00:50:04.344
rulings on that to help
curb those bad behaviors?

00:50:04.344 --> 00:50:05.260
MICHAEL WEBSTER: Yeah.

00:50:05.260 --> 00:50:09.670
So every nonprofit
organization has

00:50:09.670 --> 00:50:12.610
to decide what are the things
that they are going to work on.

00:50:12.610 --> 00:50:15.370
And what do they want
to really specialize on?

00:50:15.370 --> 00:50:17.140
We have not made a
decision to specialize

00:50:17.140 --> 00:50:18.100
on things like legislation.

00:50:18.100 --> 00:50:20.230
We actually have lots of
great peer organizations

00:50:20.230 --> 00:50:22.380
that work things like the
US national government,

00:50:22.380 --> 00:50:24.130
or national governments
in other countries

00:50:24.130 --> 00:50:26.230
to try and create
legislation for things

00:50:26.230 --> 00:50:28.400
like protected areas,
and things like that.

00:50:28.400 --> 00:50:32.080
So our work is much
more community-focused,

00:50:32.080 --> 00:50:35.060
which is part of the
overall set of solutions.

00:50:35.060 --> 00:50:37.324
It's not everything that
needs to take place.

00:50:37.324 --> 00:50:39.490
What we tend to find in
most places around the world

00:50:39.490 --> 00:50:42.670
is that sort of larger
scale legal framework

00:50:42.670 --> 00:50:45.370
is an enabling condition
which can allow conservation

00:50:45.370 --> 00:50:46.480
to proceed.

00:50:46.480 --> 00:50:50.129
By itself, it doesn't
usually get us to solutions.

00:50:50.129 --> 00:50:52.420
I would say, particularly,
in developing countries that

00:50:52.420 --> 00:50:55.330
might pass great laws, but
then they don't necessarily

00:50:55.330 --> 00:50:56.950
have the mandate
or the resources

00:50:56.950 --> 00:50:59.680
to really implement
or enforce those laws.

00:50:59.680 --> 00:51:02.090
What we find is that in
a lot of these countries,

00:51:02.090 --> 00:51:05.590
communities can then
use that legal framework

00:51:05.590 --> 00:51:08.800
to assert a set of protections
or management systems

00:51:08.800 --> 00:51:11.110
over the resources that
are important to them--

00:51:11.110 --> 00:51:13.810
oftentimes-- through some kind
of co-management structure,

00:51:13.810 --> 00:51:15.730
where the government
will say, gee.

00:51:15.730 --> 00:51:17.429
We recognize this is our law.

00:51:17.429 --> 00:51:18.970
But we're not really
implementing it.

00:51:18.970 --> 00:51:20.594
If the community
wants to implement it,

00:51:20.594 --> 00:51:22.750
we'll try and figure out
ways to work with you.

00:51:22.750 --> 00:51:25.450
So that's the space that
we work in more than the

00:51:25.450 --> 00:51:27.830
setting the legal frameworks
in the first place.

00:51:27.830 --> 00:51:29.579
A lot of the countries
we work in actually

00:51:29.579 --> 00:51:31.310
have very progressive
laws around this.

00:51:31.310 --> 00:51:33.018
If you look at like
Honduras for example,

00:51:33.018 --> 00:51:36.400
it has some very
progressive laws

00:51:36.400 --> 00:51:38.530
around protecting
coastal resources.

00:51:38.530 --> 00:51:40.420
And they've established
very large parks.

00:51:40.420 --> 00:51:43.160
And if you just look at that
on paper, you'd say, wow.

00:51:43.160 --> 00:51:44.450
This is great.

00:51:44.450 --> 00:51:46.600
The problem is that
95% of the work

00:51:46.600 --> 00:51:49.390
remains to be done after that,
which is how do you translate

00:51:49.390 --> 00:51:53.410
that into a set of durable,
effective practices

00:51:53.410 --> 00:51:58.360
that are consonant with
the community's interests,

00:51:58.360 --> 00:52:01.755
so that they'll be
maintained moving forward?

00:52:01.755 --> 00:52:03.880
In the US-- you mentioned
some of the coastal areas

00:52:03.880 --> 00:52:04.780
in the US--

00:52:04.780 --> 00:52:08.740
the US has a mixed record on
this for coral reef protection.

00:52:08.740 --> 00:52:13.060
I would say in some cases, we
see more progressive policies

00:52:13.060 --> 00:52:15.691
sometimes in developing
countries than, say, Hawaii--

00:52:15.691 --> 00:52:17.440
particularly around
things like fisheries.

00:52:17.440 --> 00:52:22.360
Hawaii has a lot of difficulty
in changing fisheries' rules,

00:52:22.360 --> 00:52:23.890
because there's a
lot of user groups

00:52:23.890 --> 00:52:26.180
who all currently
access the resource.

00:52:26.180 --> 00:52:28.260
And none of them want to
give up that resource.

00:52:28.260 --> 00:52:30.093
And that makes sense
from their perspective,

00:52:30.093 --> 00:52:34.000
but it creates an ongoing
problem on the reef.

00:52:34.000 --> 00:52:37.707
The US does have some big
coral reef protected areas.

00:52:37.707 --> 00:52:39.790
Hawaii is interesting,
because a lot of the really

00:52:39.790 --> 00:52:41.331
degraded reefs in
Hawaii are the ones

00:52:41.331 --> 00:52:45.040
you would see if you went to
Oahu, or Maui, or Hawaii island

00:52:45.040 --> 00:52:46.150
and went snorkeling.

00:52:46.150 --> 00:52:48.490
Those are the high islands
of Hawaii, which is

00:52:48.490 --> 00:52:50.230
where most people would visit.

00:52:50.230 --> 00:52:51.650
If you go past
those high islands,

00:52:51.650 --> 00:52:54.130
there's actually a series
of atolls that go far,

00:52:54.130 --> 00:52:56.860
far up into the North Pacific.

00:52:56.860 --> 00:53:00.020
So here are the high islands
of Hawaii right in here.

00:53:00.020 --> 00:53:02.020
And then, there's
this Long Island chain

00:53:02.020 --> 00:53:05.920
which is sometimes called the
Northwest Hawaiian Islands.

00:53:05.920 --> 00:53:09.740
Actually, George W. Bush turned
it into a national monument.

00:53:09.740 --> 00:53:13.300
It's called Papahanaumokuakea,
which essentially protected

00:53:13.300 --> 00:53:15.890
that entire set of islands--

00:53:15.890 --> 00:53:18.880
that entire chain of islands--
which is one of the biggest

00:53:18.880 --> 00:53:20.800
protected areas on
the planet, and one

00:53:20.800 --> 00:53:23.055
of the most significant
ones for coral reefs.

00:53:23.055 --> 00:53:25.430
And then, it was expanded
under the Obama administration.

00:53:25.430 --> 00:53:28.250
We'll see if it holds.

00:53:28.250 --> 00:53:31.180
AUDIENCE: So you mentioned that
you have basically more demand

00:53:31.180 --> 00:53:33.680
for getting your constitution
working with these communities

00:53:33.680 --> 00:53:34.520
than you can handle.

00:53:34.520 --> 00:53:36.620
So I was just
wondering, what are

00:53:36.620 --> 00:53:37.994
your thoughts in trying to--

00:53:37.994 --> 00:53:39.410
I guess-- scale
your organization,

00:53:39.410 --> 00:53:42.170
or the number of communities
that you are reaching out to?

00:53:42.170 --> 00:53:44.290
MICHAEL WEBSTER: Yeah.

00:53:44.290 --> 00:53:46.820
There's a number of
different dimensions to that.

00:53:46.820 --> 00:53:49.880
One is, we work with lots
of other organizations.

00:53:49.880 --> 00:53:52.280
And we have a fundamental
belief in partnerships,

00:53:52.280 --> 00:53:54.022
that the Coral
Reef Alliance isn't

00:53:54.022 --> 00:53:55.730
going to solve these
problems on our own.

00:53:55.730 --> 00:53:57.554
And it's silly for
us to think so.

00:53:57.554 --> 00:53:59.720
Instead, we work with lots
of different conservation

00:53:59.720 --> 00:54:04.127
organizations to try and get
to this scale collectively.

00:54:04.127 --> 00:54:05.960
Another piece of it is
we need to figure out

00:54:05.960 --> 00:54:07.515
how to replicate efficiently.

00:54:07.515 --> 00:54:09.890
Because if you have to start
over in every place and say,

00:54:09.890 --> 00:54:11.150
OK, now it's a new problem--

00:54:11.150 --> 00:54:12.650
let's begin from zero--

00:54:12.650 --> 00:54:15.290
then you're using basically
the maximum resources

00:54:15.290 --> 00:54:16.836
to get the job done
in any one place.

00:54:16.836 --> 00:54:18.710
And so we're always
looking for opportunities

00:54:18.710 --> 00:54:22.310
to take ideas that
worked in one place

00:54:22.310 --> 00:54:25.935
and use them to build sort of
word of mouth momentum, where

00:54:25.935 --> 00:54:27.560
the community next
door looks and says,

00:54:27.560 --> 00:54:29.210
hey, I want one of those.

00:54:29.210 --> 00:54:30.790
Why can't we do that?

00:54:30.790 --> 00:54:32.660
And at the same time,
build those tools

00:54:32.660 --> 00:54:35.600
that are transportable-- so
that in the next community,

00:54:35.600 --> 00:54:38.120
you have a built in
already interest in trying

00:54:38.120 --> 00:54:39.650
the same kind of solution.

00:54:39.650 --> 00:54:42.020
You've got tools and
techniques for doing it.

00:54:42.020 --> 00:54:44.760
You can implement the
same thing more cheaply.

00:54:44.760 --> 00:54:47.474
So there's some scalability
that's built around that.

00:54:47.474 --> 00:54:48.890
The other piece
is as a nonprofit,

00:54:48.890 --> 00:54:50.723
we're also always looking
for more resources

00:54:50.723 --> 00:54:52.430
to implement at scale.

00:54:52.430 --> 00:54:54.650
There's not going to be
a silver bullet here.

00:54:54.650 --> 00:54:57.770
There isn't going to be just a
viral solution that can cruise

00:54:57.770 --> 00:54:58.854
and expand all on its own.

00:54:58.854 --> 00:55:00.270
At the end of the
day, it is going

00:55:00.270 --> 00:55:02.150
to take a certain
amount of heavy lifting

00:55:02.150 --> 00:55:05.180
in a lot of communities to get
to these kinds of solutions.

00:55:05.180 --> 00:55:07.760
The question is, how do we do
that in a coordinated way that

00:55:07.760 --> 00:55:09.801
takes advantage of all
the different players that

00:55:09.801 --> 00:55:11.750
are out there, and in
each and every instance

00:55:11.750 --> 00:55:13.880
does it as efficiently
and effectively

00:55:13.880 --> 00:55:15.970
as possible with the
minimum amount of resources,

00:55:15.970 --> 00:55:18.451
so we can apply those
resources somewhere else?

00:55:18.451 --> 00:55:19.200
Thanks, everybody.

00:55:19.200 --> 00:55:22.550
[APPLAUSE]

